  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Critically, this process in non-destructive allowing specimens to be preserved, though sample reduction via cutting or coring may be necessary to achieve the desired resolution (i.e., due to beam attenuation or resolution limits imposed by beam geometry).",
    "The resultant volume image provides a grayscale map of X-ray attenuation, which can be related to sample physical properties (principally density / material atomic number).",
    "Classic Hounsfield CT setups commonly used in medical imaging, which incorporate a gantry housing the X-ray tube and detector designed to rotate around the target object during imaging can accommodate large macrofossil specimens, typically providing sub-millimeter resolution (e.g., Golder and Christian (2002)).",
    "Microfocus industrial and lab based systems, as well as synchrotron X-ray tomographic beamlines can provide much higher resolution tomographic images (Echlin 2011), typically using higher energy X-rays, providing microtomographic (µCT) or even nanotomographic (nCT) capabilities, with resolutions in the tens to few micron, submicron and few tens of nanometer range respectively.",
    "Typically, this improved resolution limits the sample size that can be mounted, with sample preparation often becoming prohibitively challenging, particularity in the case of nano CT."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
